[[File:Master Polikarp's Dialog with Death.jpg|thumb|Title page of ''Åmierci z Mistrzem dwojakie gadania...'' (contains ''Master Polikarp's Dialog with Death''), Maciej Scharffenberg edition, ca. 1542]] '''Master Polikarp's Dialog with Death''' (Polish: '''''Rozmowa Mistrza Polikarpa ze ÅmierciÄ ''''', Latin: '''''De morte prologus, Dialogus inter Mortem et Magistrum Polikarpum''''') is a late [[Middle Ages|medieval]] dialog in verse, written probably in the early 15th century. Master Polikarp's Dialog with Death is now regarded as one of the most important examples of [[medieval poetry]] in the [[Polish language]]. The work is patterned after a 12th century [[Latin]] poem ''Dialogus mortis cum homine'', and other Latin language publications, popular in medieval Europe. Its author is unknown, but after discovering the complete, printed version from 1542 some [[historian]]s speculate that [[MikoÅaj Rej]] has re-written the original text for print.
One of the unique features of the work is its use of [[humour]]. The dialog mocks monks and priests, inn-keepers, fat women, dishonest physicians and unjust judges.
== Versions ==
The original version of the [[dialogue]] has been lost; what remains is an incomplete copy from ca. 1463-1465, belonging to MikoÅaj of Mirzyniec (MikoÅaj z MirzyÅca). The ending of the work was known due to its 16th century [[Russian language|Russian]] [[translation]]. It has 498 lines, and presents everyday life scenes of members of different social classes of 15th century [[Poland]].
An unknown printed edition of ''Rozmowa Mistrza Polikarpa ze ÅmierciÄ '' (''Master Polikarpâs Dialogue with Death'') from 1542 (Cracow, Maciej [[Scharffenberg family|Scharffenberg]]) has been discovered in one of the European university libraries.<ref name="a">{{Cite web | url=https://instytutksiazki.pl/en/news,2,professor-wydra%E2%80%99s-great-discovery,1307.html | |title=Professor Wydraâs Great Discovery | publisher = The Polish Book Institute | date= July 3, 2018 | access-date=November 8, 2018}}</ref> The discovery was made by Professor WiesÅaw Wydra from the Institute of Polish Philology at [[Adam Mickiewicz University]] in [[PoznaÅ]].<ref name="a"/> In the contrast to the previously known version of the dialogue from the PÅock manuscript, this text has been preserved in its entirety.<ref name="a"/> This discovery, with a complete Polish text of 918 verses, makes it the biggest and the most important event in Polish language and literature scholarship for several decades.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.thefirstnews.com/article/full-text-of-polish-literatures-oldest-masterpiece-found-1138 | title=Full text of Polish literatureâs oldest masterpiece found | last=Nowacki | first = Aleksander | publisher = The first news | date= July 14, 2018 | access-date=November 8, 2018}}</ref> The critical edition of the discovered text has been published by prof. WiesÅaw Wydra and became available on 7th November 2018.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://psp.amu.edu.pl/?type=news&id_asset=1150 | title=NiezwykÅe odkrycie | publisher = Wydawnictwo "PoznaÅskie Studia Polonistyczne" UAM | date=July 3, 2018 | access-date=November 8, 2018}}</ref> {{expand-section|date=November 2018}}
== Characters == * Master Polikarp â a well-educated person, * Death â pale, skinny, bald, yellowish, without nose and lips, showing its ribs, naked, a rotten kind of a woman. It holds a scepter in its hands, and its resemblance reminds the reader that life is short, and after death, human bodies decay. {{expand-section|date=November 2018}}
